<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Andrew Bodman (HSR 002)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt">Written evidence from</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt"> Andrew Bodman (HSR 002)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">1. The latest version of the HS2 Economic Case published at the end of October 2013 still contains faults </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">some of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">which have been pointed out in earlier versions. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Some other shortcomings are detailed too.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The benefits of HS2 have been significantly overstated again, and in at least two cases using arguments that have been previously discredited.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The route still has a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> designed in bottleneck between Birmingham and London</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The most serious problem the rail network faces in this country is overcrowding on commuter trains particularly into London from the south and east. HS2 will not address this issue.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The disruption effec</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ts created by the construction of HS2 have not been detailed while those for an alternative scheme have been grossly overstated.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">No provision has</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> been made for handling a doubling</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> of passe</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ngers who will need to use the U</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">nderground at Euston during the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">peak</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> hour. It is not responsible</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> to suggest</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> that it is someone else’s problem.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Evidence for regional regeneration would suggest that if there </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">were</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> any beneficiary that it </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">would</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> be London.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Many countries have found that the debts incurred in building a high spe</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ed rail network are considerable and take a long time to pay off. The situation is not helped by the ongoing subsidy required to run these high speed lines.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The experience of other countries suggests that investment in high speed rail means that investment</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> in classic rail is neglected.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">2. My recommendation is to cancel HS2 now. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Overstated Benefits</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">3. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The economic case still uses</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the basis that people do not work on trains and therefore any journey time saving results in added work (productivity). While</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the value of time has been changed, the principle that a shorter journey time leads to more worker output has not changed. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">It is well known that many people work on trains whether using a laptop, iPad, smartphone or simply reading documents. To continue t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">o ignore what happens in the real world is absurd.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">4. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Previously the Department for Transport had anticipated that about 30% of HS2 passengers would be on business. National Passenger Surveys have regularly reported a similar proportion of business travellers on intercity routes on the West Coast Mainline (WC</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ML), Midland Mainline (MML) and East Coast Mainline (ECML). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.passengerfocus.org.uk/research/national-passenger-survey-introduction"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.passengerfocus.org.uk/research/national-passenger-survey-introduction</span></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">    See Stakeholde</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">r Report</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">5. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The latest HS2 economic case now anticipates a much higher proportion of business travellers than previously, e.g. 66% for London Manchester. Such a high proportion of business travellers </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">is no longer in line with National Passenger Surveys.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">6. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The HS2 economic case for HS2 is still calculated on the basis that passenger </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ticket prices will carry no premium over those for classic rail journeys. This lack of premium ticket pricing in the DfT’s HS2 passenger demand modelling was strongly challeng</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ed by the Public Accounts Committee in 2012. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmpubacc/464/12041801.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmpubacc/464/12041801.htm</span></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">   See questions 42 to 50</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and their answers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">7. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Currently there is a 20% ticket price premium for Ashford to London travellers on HS1 compared to a classic rail journey. In Europe, the ticket price premium is typically 70%. Recently the Secretary of State for Transport was quoted </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">as saying </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in the context of HS2, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="color:#1e1e1e; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">If you turn up at the last minute, you are going to be paying a lot of money.”</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/road-and-rail-transport/10302224/HS2-Passengers-will-have-to-pay-a-lot-of-money-unless-they-book-ahead.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/road-and-rail-transport/10302224/HS2-Passengers-will-have-to-pay-a-lot-of-money-unless-they-book-ahead.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">8. If you take a 20% premium over Virgin trains for a return Birmingham London journey at</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> peak times, you </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">theoretically </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">have the following alternatives</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> at 2013 prices:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Chiltern Railways</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">  £95</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Virgin Trains</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">£158</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">HS2</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">£189</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">9. Ticket pricing does have an effect on demand, and to construct a HS2 passenger forecast without a price premium l</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">eads to overs</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">tated level of passenger demand.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">10. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">All of the factors listed above result in a grossly overstated amount of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">benefits. Independent bodies</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> suggest a realistic be</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">nefit cost ratio for HS2 is 0.5, i.e. 50p back for every £1 spent.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">That would be </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">unsatisfactory by Treasury rules as well as being an irresponsible use of taxpayers’ money.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Designed in Bottleneck</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">11. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Many of the main </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">rail </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">lines serving London are close to the maximum number of train paths that they can accommodate at peak times. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Ultr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">a high speed trains require g</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">reater stopping distances than</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> classic trains as a result of their greater kinetic energy. So an ultra high speed line can accommodate fewer trains per hour than a classic line. The UIC (International Union of Railways) has indicated that it is not safe to run more than 16 trains per h</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">our at 350 kph. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">See Figure 2</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.greengauge21.net/wp-content/uploads/Final-Report-Appendices-B-J.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.greengauge21.net/wp-content/uploads/Final-Report-Appendices-B-J.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">12. The indicative schedule for HS2 phase two shows</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> 16 trains per hour planned for the Birmingham Interchange to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">the junction for the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Heathrow spur section of the route. See figure 6-2 in PFMv4.3 Assumptions Report. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://assets.hs2.org.uk/sites/default/files/inserts/S%26A%2020_PFM%20assumptions%20report.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://assets.hs2.org.uk/sites/default/files/inserts/S%26A%2020_PFM%20assumptions%20report.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">13. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">In addition</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> there are tentatively two trains</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">per hour to serve Heathrow. Lastly there are two more trains per hour to link with HS1 and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">presumably these go further north than Heathrow; this is in addition to the Old Oak Common service to HS1 service. So this shows that up to t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">wenty trains per hour are intended on a </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">section of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">line that can</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> safely handle </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">only </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">16 trains per hour. In other wo</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">rds there is an intention to spend £50 billion on a line that has no room for expansion s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ven years after it is built. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The Victorians had considerably more foresight.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> Contractor Atkins was aware of this issue in 2008 and documented it in their report “Beca</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">use Transport Matters”.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://stophs2.org/news/7424-is-dft-misleading-us-part-2"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://stophs2.org/news/7424-is-dft-misleading-us-part-2</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Existing Commuter Overcrowding</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">14. However HS2 does not address the most pressing problems that the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">rail network currently experiences, which is that of overcrowded commuter trains. Over 120,000 rail passengers stand on trains during the morning peak three hours every weekday; DfT data for typical autumn day 2012.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/rail-passenger-numbers-and-crowding-on-weekdays-in-major-cities-in-england-and-wales-2012"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/rail-passenger-numbers-and-crowding-on-weekdays-in-major-cities-in-england-and-wales-2012</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">15. The worst </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">affected lines </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in terms of trains carrying standing passengers </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">are those serving the following stations:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">London Bridge</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">31,247</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Waterloo</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">28,168</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Victoria</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">14,337</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Liverpool Street</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">12,205</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Fenchurch Street</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">  8,143</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">tc.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">16. A Transport for London study in 2007 </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">found that 85% of rail passengers travelling to London come from East Anglia and the South East.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">17. In the last ten years </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">there has been a far greater growth in rail passenger numbers in London and the South East than there has in long distance.</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:260pt"><tr style="height:18pt"><td colspan="4" style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:bottom; width:260pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Rail </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">passenger journeys (millions)</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:45pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; bo