ia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">19. Euston had just 2,821 standing passengers and the majority of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">these were on London Overground and London Midland trains. Virgin Trains carry just 2% of national rail passengers. So why build an ultra high speed intercity line serving the North West when its trains are s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ome of the least overcrowded,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the vast majority </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">of travellers to London don’t come from that direction</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and the biggest growth of passenger numbers has been for commuters </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in the London area</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">?</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> The impro</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ved Thameslink service </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in 2018 </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">will only</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> address a small proportion of these overcrowding issues.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Disrup</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">tion effects</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">20. While being ready to criticise alternatives to HS2 due to the disruption that they will supposedly cause, the DfT has not indicated how much disruption will be caused by the construction of HS2 itself.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">21. The building of HS2 will cause </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">very </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">severe disruption at Euston for approximately 9 years. It is likely that Euston station will be closed for some weekends and for some bank holiday periods. The number of platforms serving classic rail will be permanently reduced from 18 to 13 and the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">number of approach tracks from 6 to 4. This will almost certainly reduce the peak time capacity o</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">f Euston on a permanent basis (for classic trains).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.railnews.co.uk/news/2013/04/19-hs2-set-to-abandon-complete.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.railnews</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">.co.uk/news/2013/04/19-hs2-set-to-abandon-complete.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">22. There will be severe disruption in Camden. This will affect London Overground services which carry 25,000 passengers daily. It will also affect freight operations on the most important cross L</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ondon freight route. It will also cause traffic chaos and se</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">riously impact Camden Market. HS2</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> will also have effects on the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">existing </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">rail network where it joins other routes such as at north of St Pancras (HS1), Old Oak Common, north of Lichfield, Crewe, n</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ear Wigan, Toton and Church Fenton. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">23. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">In addition HS2’s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> construction will affect road users for an extended period with the need to cross the M1 (6</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">times), M42 (6 times), M56 (3 times), M6 (3 times) and M62 (2 times) as well as 47 crossings of trunk ro</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ads.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> To bring about its construction, many large trucks will be using any roads from motorways to narrow country lanes for several years.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.cpre.org.uk/what-we-do/transport/rail/update/item/3391-striking-new-hs2-maps-launched"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.cpre.org.uk/what-we-do/transport/rail/update/item/3391-striking-new-hs2-maps-launched</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">24. By contrast the 51M Optimised Alternative which does meet the DfT’s forecast passenger growth requirements </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">(through an increase of standard class capac</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ity on each train) </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">would need work at just three points on the WCML. Grade separated junctions </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">would need to be built </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">at Ledburn and Colwich, and laying of additional track to increase freight capacity between Rugby and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Nuneaton. For the latter, weekend se</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">rvices could be diverted via other rail routes while the work is undertaken. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The 51M Optimised Alternative requires no disruption at Euston, Camden or the other places which will be affected by the construction of HS2. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Talk of 14 years of weekend working i</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s nothing other than unfounded scaremongering. A journalist can see through that deception.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/road-and-rail-transport/10423076/Lies-at-the-heart-of-case-for-HS2.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/r</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">oad-and-rail-transport/10423076/Lies-at-the-heart-of-case-for-HS2.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Omissions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">25. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">It has been estimated that HS2 will provide an extra 10,000 passengers per hour into the Underground network at Euston in addition to the existing 7000 per hour at peak periods. Source: Section 3.6, (page 20) HS2 Ltd Route Engineering Report.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">(This appea</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">rs to be no longer available on the internet, although I still have a copy)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">26. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">As is well known, the Underground is another British railway system that is very short of capacity at peak times. To more than double the demand at Euston without providing add</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">itional Underground capacity is unworkable. As Transport for London has pointed out, it will require the building of Crossrail 2.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> This has not been included in the HS2 budget.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Regional Regeneration</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">27. Several independent people </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">or organisations </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">have stu</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">died the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">regional </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">effects of high speed rail in other countries. Professor Tomaney provided comprehensive oral and written evidence to this committee in 2011 on the subject of high speed rail. His views were that the amount of regional regeneration being c</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">reated would be small, and if it did exist then the regional beneficiary would be the capital</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> in this case London. Other independent studies of actual evidence have reached similar conclusions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201012/cmselect/cmtran/1185/11071201.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201012/cmselect/cmtran/1185/11071201.htm</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201012/cmselect/cmtran/writev/rail/m14.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.publications.parliament</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">.uk/pa/cm201012/cmselect/cmtran/writev/rail/m14.htm</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Debt and Subsidy</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">28. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The UK has a national debt of approximately £1.2 trillion. Network Rail ha</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s a debt of £30 billion which some expect</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> to rise to £50 billion by 2020.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">29. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The debt that China has incurring in building its high speed lines reached US $ 640 billion by the end of 2012.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/27/business/global/worlds-longest-high-speed-rail-line-opens-in-china.html?_r=0"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.nytimes</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">.com/2012/12/27/business/global/worlds-longest-high-speed-rail-line-opens-in-china.html?_r=0</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#fcfff5; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">30. </span><span style="background-color:#fcfff5; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Zhao Jian, a professor at Beijing Jiaotong University, said he worries that the cost of the project might have created a hidden debt bomb that threatens Ch</span><span style="background-color:#fcfff5; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ina’s banking system.</span><span style="background-color:#fcfff5; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#fcfff5; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">“In China, we will have a debt crisis — a high-speed rail debt </span><span style="background-color:#fcfff5; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">crisis,” he told the Washington Post. “I think it is more serious than your subprime mortgage crisis. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://factsanddetails.com/china/cat13/sub86/item1848.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://factsanddetails.com/china/cat13/sub86/item1848.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">31. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Japan was the pioneer of high speed rail in the 1960s but within two decades had accumulated massive debts. The system was privatised and the $280 billion debt was transferred to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">the taxpayer and is still being paid off. Apparently four of the seven operators are still government owned, and it is thought that the privately owned operators receive concessionary usage fees. In addition, the three private operators receive another $2 </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">billion annually from the government. These subsidises are needed despite Japan having the highest rate of rail use in the developed world.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.cc-hsr.org/assets/pdf/bnote-10.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.cc-hsr.org/assets/pdf/bnote-10.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.policymic.com/articles/1512/high-speed-rail-hardly-an-investment-in-future"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.policymic.com/articles/1512/high-speed-rail-hardly-an-investment-in-future</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.heritage.org/research/reports/2010/03/america-s-coming-high-speed-rail-financial-disaster"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.heritage.org/research/reports/2010/03/america-s-coming-high-speed-rail-financial-disaster</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">32. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The French accounting system treats taxpayer subsidies as “commercial revenues”. So the French programme’s $1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.75 billion “profit” occurs through a $10 billion annual subsidy according to a study by Amtrak in 2008. The national rail infrastructure assets were transferred to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Réseau Ferré de France (RFF) in 1997. Between RFF and SNCF there was an accumulated debt of</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> €38 billion from building lines for the TGV by 2011. To deal with this debt, RFF is expected to increase track fees by 40% between 2008 and 2012 to reduce this debt. SNCF has threatened to cancel low ridership routes and has indicated that its reduced pro</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">fitability will make it impossible to renew its 1981 fleet of TGVs before 2020. TGV fares are being increased by more than twice the rate of inflation and in some cases even more.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.thetransportpolitic.com/2011/09/24/after-30-years-tgv-service-prospers-even-as-its-future-is-questioned/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.thetransportpolitic.com/2011/09/24/after-30-years-tgv-service-prospers-even-as-its-future-is-questioned/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">33. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">It </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">is understood that Spain spends nearly $3 billion on high speed rail subsidies annually and Germany more than $1 billion per year. We also know that t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">he high speed line between Amsterdam, Rotterdam </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">and Breda (in the Netherlands) was</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> saved from bankruptcy w</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ith a </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">£250m government bailout. It had</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> been losing £320,000 per day due to disastrous levels of patronage.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://capoliticalnews.com/2012/04/15/grimes-new-high-speed-rail-biz-plan-crashes-into-reality/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://capoliticalnews.com/2012/04/15</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">/grimes-new-high-speed-rail-biz-plan-crashes-into-reality/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://money.cnn.com/2009/06/10/news/economy/high_speed_rail/index.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://money.cnn.com/2009/06/10/news/economy/high_speed_rail/index.htm</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/road-and-rail-transport/9000166/High-speed-rail-A-250m-lesson-for-Britains-rail-enthusiasts.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/road-and-rail-transport/9000166/High-speed-rail-A-250m-lesson-for-Britains-rail-enthusiasts.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">34. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">This over-estimation of passenger demand leads to debts and subsidies being required from governments. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">In July 2010 a World Bank report cautioned that governments planning high-speed rail</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">systems:  </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“. . should also contemplate the near-certainty of cop</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ious and continuing budget</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">support for the debt”.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">See summary page 1.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/WDSP/IB/2010/07/26/000334955_20100726032714/Rendered/PDF/558560WP0Box341SR1v08121jul101final.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/WDSP/IB/2010/07/26/000334955_20100726032714/Rendered/PDF/558560WP0Box341SR1v08121jul101final.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">35. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Some countries have seen the light; Poland has decided not to build a high speed rail ne</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">twork, Portugal has abandoned plans to build three high speed lines one of which would have linked to Spain.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> In June 2013, France shelved all TGV projects not currently under construction for 17 years.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/polish-high-speed-rail-project-cancelled.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/polish-high-speed-rail-project-cancelled.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/high-speed-rail-u-turn/27691"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.the</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">portugalnews.com/news/high-speed-rail-u-turn/27691</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/france-shunts-new-tgv-projects-into-a-siding-8676909.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/france-shunts-new-tgv-projects-into-a</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">-siding-8676909.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Adverse effect on classic rail</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">36. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The president of</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the SNCF, Guillaume Pépy thought that France wa</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s going too fast in its further construction of high speed lines. TGV fares have increased by 100% in the last decade compared to about 30% for car travel. Pépy went on to say: </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The whole basis of the high-speed rail revolution – that the TGV should be the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">"normal" means of travel, not just something affordable by the business elite – is under threat. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The SNCF president also described the state railways as: </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Decaying... facing a financial impasse... and heading for the wall. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">He should know better than most.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/life-on-the-fast-track-thirty-years-of-the-tgv-2265455.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/life-on-the-fast-track-thirty-years-of-the-tgv-2265455.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">37. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Millions of people u</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">sing commuter lines every day, particularly around Paris, have suffered years of overcrowding, dirty trains and unreliable lines. Pépy said there is an urgent need to increase capacity on these lines. Following a fatal rail accident outside Paris in July 2</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">013, the Transport Minister Fr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">é</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">é</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ric Cuvillier commented that regional lines had been underfunded for many years as investment went to high-speed lines.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/622bcdc2-779a-11e2-b95a-00144feabdc0.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ft.com/cms/</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">s/0/622bcdc2-779a-11e2-b95a-00144feabdc0.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a href="http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/europe/article3816469.ece"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/europe/article3816469.ece</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">38. While significant spending </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">for rail </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">is planned </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in the UK </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">for Control Period 5 (2014 – 19), there is nothing to say that such a level of spending is affordable on an ongoing basis alongside HS2. It should not be forgotten that our classic rail will continue to transport most of our rail passengers; such</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> lines need regular maintenance and many parts of the country seek further enhancements e.g. electrification from Bristol to the South West.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About the author</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">39. I have been studying High Speed Two in fine detail for more than two years. I live at least 1</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">6 miles from the proposed route. I am a director of HS2 Action Alliance and a member of South Northants Action Group. This submission is my own and is not on behalf of any other organisation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">40. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">I believe HS2 will not address the most pressing issue of o</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">vercrowded commuter trains to the south and east of London. If the Government is determined to increase the capacity for users of the West Coast Main Line, then it should adopt the 51M Optimised Alternative which is far cheaper</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, can be introduced much soon</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">er and with less disruption than HS2. There is no logical basis for spending £50 (+) billion to supplement the capacity of a line which carries </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">just </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">2% of our rail passengers and does not have the standing passenger issues which ma</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ny other lines have. How </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">will HS2</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> be helping the other 98% of rail travellers? HS2 is a totally ill conceived project and many people have not even studied the finer details.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> If they did, they would understand its many </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">fundamental </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">shortcomings.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>